segments.text: Jay Wayne would go to see anybody about anything to benefit his program, financially or to help a student or whatever.
It was a pure orientation.
It wasn't to benefit himself in any way.
I've not seen anybody live in a more frugal home.
His salary was not that great.
He didn't do it for money.
I did it for power, but power to help students.
And so I respected them.
Never, never at any time ever thought that I would be better off with someone else in that position.
I did think that about a lot of other positions, but never and never.
I'm not going to ask the negative one.
Other than Wayne Stark, who were described your favorite...
staff, your subordinate colleagues?
Oh, I had in my office starting out, I had Howard Perry and Bob Melcher.
And they were two super, super guys.
Of course, the year later, we added Ormond Simpson.
So I had three Aggies.
Oh, and Malin, of course, was in my office at that time, too.
I had four A's to kind of keep me on a straight and narrow to make sure that I didn't screw up.
They were all wonderful and different in their own way.
Bob Melcher, well, Bob Melcher and Malin were both seen by the student body initially as spies.
They thought student leaders that came to see me as soon after I got here.
Was it Melcher and Malin just come around to see things to tell
General Hannigan, and he was in trouble.
What were their nicknames?
Oh, God, I can't, I've forgotten.
Malin was the Slink.
Yeah.
And was Melcher the Wedge?
I've forgotten.
Because according to the students, Malin slinked around to snoop on them.
Yeah.
But those guys in the office...
Oh, and another one.
O.L.
Luther.
O.L.
headed up University Police and O.L.
was a former Texas Ranger.
He was a wonderful guy.
Terrible administrator.
Just a wonderful human being.
But, so, Tom Parsons.
Tom was a good man.
I liked Tom.
I enjoyed working with Tom.
Tom had a lot of
negative things happen family-wise to him in terms of his wife and his family.
But he was a Texas Aggie through and through and through.
He was a good administrator.
He would do anything to help a youngster as well.
I think Jay Wayne's attitude
You know, that was the same attitude that Ormond Simpson had, Malin had, and Bob Elcher had, and Howard Curry had.
And people didn't see that, but that was the cream that came to the top for me.
It's related to those individuals.
Now, some who had that had some difficulties with administrative kinds of things, and just like O.L.,
I finally decided that what we would do was to have Bob Melcher do the administrative types of things as it related to University Police.
And Orwell would pick up on the personal relationships and so on.
So you work around that.
They were good people, good human beings.
All right.
Early on, did you sense there were any problems that were here when you arrived that you had to tackle?
Quickly.
Anything you had to clean up, straighten up?
Not really in regard to anything that Jim had left behind.
I think the fraternity-sorority thing was something that we wanted to work on on a continuing basis at that particular time.
Oh.
Women in the Corps, that was the first year.
And so that was something we had to continue to work on.
When you arrived, there were no women in the Corps?
Yet.
Tom had integrated that, well he had agreed to integrate that spring.
So it was that first fall that I was here.
Fall of 73.
That we had women in the Corps for the first time.
And do you recall how that went that first fall?
Some pluses or minuses?
The interesting thing is that
I'm reminded of this time after time with the Citadel and the institutions in Virginia.
You're going to have some women who get upset about the manner in which they're treated.
And they're not...
My perception of a female in the Corps of Cadets or in the military is one that's sort of tomboyish, that they like the physical kinds of things.
And they handle the Corps well.
But there are some who don't like the physical things, and it's amazing why they get interested in the Corps, but then are very resentful.
And so way back in the beginning,
young ladies dropping out of the Corps who would really raise team about what had been done to them.
And that was a continuing thing all the way up until I retired.
And it's still ongoing now.
We had a number of wonderful young ladies.
I saw an article just in the paper the other day about the first woman who graduated
who spent four years in the Corps at A&M, is retiring as a major.
That was in the newspaper.
In Eagle?
Well, it was in Eagle within the past few days.
I don't know if it's Eagle.
It may have been in a column.
I need to chase her down, because she'd be a good interview subject.
Let's see.
To get back to your question, I really didn't feel under the gun about anything.
You know, nothing that just stuck its neck out.
Alright, now let's reach out across the campus.
Your key administrative associates outside Student Life, who were the key people
First of all, we're Tom Cherry, Clyde Freeman, John Calhoun.
And in talking to John, I decided that the best way that I could get to know all the economic folks was to attend his dean's meeting every time.
That was super for me because I got to know everyone.
to know what the institution was all about.
In that group, of course, Frank Huber, strong in education.
Fred Benson, an engineer.
Mac Breska, and the reason I giggle about Mac, first time I met Mac was by telephone.
He called me and he was fussing about somebody had parked in his parking place and he wanted the damn police to come over and pull that damn car out.
And so,
I went over to visit with Mac after that and got to know Mac.
So, the Deans, John Pearson in business.
Oh golly, over in Liberal Arts with David... Maxwell.
Maxwell.
Veterinary Medicine.
George Shelton and I were hired on the same day by the board and so George and
Ah, George.
I can't think of his wife's name.
Joy.
I keep thinking of Joy.
George and Joy became good friends and we have remained good friends ever since.
Oh, geosciences.
Earl.
Cook.
I really liked the academic beings.
You and
and Dick were also included in that particular group.
My relationship I thought was a good one, and I thought everyone was very kind to me in regard to helping me understand the institution and all the programs going on, and were very supportive.
So all that was excellent.
And I'm sure that John was the one that, you know,
leader in that, although you and Dick may have been as well because you all were super to me too.
As far as I was aware, everything went well when you arrived.
We saw things going smoothly.
All right, let's see.
Do you remember any hot colds rolling out of the fireplace in your early year or so?
some problem that had to have immediate attention?
Oh, the first one was a crazy one.
And that was we had the nudes.
That first fall, we had the nudes running around the campus.
That became a problem.
I'm trying to think of the slang word.
Not stripping.
So the word we were looking for is streaking.
Go ahead.
That evening that they had the streaking, there were a few people arrested.
And a large number of students went to the President's house.
I was out of town.
In fact, I was up at East Texas.
I'd been invited back up to Commerce for something.
And so Howard Perry called me.
I don't believe that Dr. Williams ever turned on a light, ever came to the door to respond.
It was dissipated by the University Police.
But there was a picture of an individual in western garb, normal western clothing with a rope
getting ready to lasso an individual on a motorcycle who was in the nude.
Do you remember that?
That's the door.
That's the security system on the door.
We worked through that one.
That didn't last very long at our campus.
Again, I think
When I say our campus is conservative, I think we have everything that A&M, that any campus has, any place across the country.
But I think we, in regard to, for example, like drugs, I think we have fewer that participate in drugs.
I think we always had fewer who would go off on the deep end on whatever issue.
And so therefore,
I think the campus would bounce back to normal very soon after anything happened.
Let's grab the drug topic.
When do you remember drugs being an item here?
Well, it was an item here since I came.
Was it?
But it had been an item in East Texas and it had been an item all over the country.
What were the drugs of choice in your first years?
I think marijuana was the big thing and acid and stuff that made you high.
I can't think of enough.
Not a real strong drug that people would get on.
But yeah, those were problems.
The major problem at A&M forever, and I guess will forever be, is alcohol.
And there are too many things tied in with tradition in alcohol at A&M, and so therefore,
probably that's the biggest problem.
One year went by, we didn't have an alcohol-related death one time or another.
All right, if you had omniscient power, omnipotent power also, all-knowing and all-power, could that be solved?
Alcohol?
I don't think it ever will be.
I agree.
I think with young people, it's something that they go through.
There are a whole lot of things that you go through as you're growing up.
My feelings about the students at A&M, no different than East Texas or wherever, if you can get them through that period of time without having them destroy themselves and their lives,
then they were going to be okay after that.
But there's going to be some experimentation in a lot of different things in a lot of different ways.
And if you can just kind of get them through it without just falling apart or having them get killed.
Can you generalize about who are the most susceptible drug and or alcohol students?
My perception, to ask you,
of all the kids that came to A&M, those kids whose parents were too rigid with them at home were the ones that kind of went off at the extreme when they came to the campus.
Now, that's not objective.
I don't have a whole lot of research on that.
But in talking to lots and lots and lots of students, those whose parents were too rigid at home kind of just got off
off track when he came.
All right, could you generalize about whether rich or poor, urban or rural?
I think it was all of those.
I think it just, the family being too rigid about rules and regulations, you know, be it urban or rural, Catholic, Baptist, whatever.
They have a tendency to go off on escapades to begin with, with alcohol.
Alright, we start about streaking.
Other problems that you remember in your first years?
I mentioned women in the Corps.
Began to occur the gays back at that time.
gay students would come to visit with me about the possibility of starting an organization.
So that problem began to... Was that early?
Uh-huh.
And it had been a problem at East Texas before I left there.
So that wasn't, so it wasn't like it was a problem here and not any place else.
I think generally that was beginning to happen.
Do you remember discussing that matter with Dr. Williams and or the board?
Dr. Williams, not the board, at the beginning.
I felt at that time, because of the state legislation relating
to groups who attempted to perpetuate those things which were illegal, it was inappropriate for us as an institution to recognize those groups.
And that was the stance that I took and recommended to Dr. Williams and the board as we got into it.
were dead against anything related to women in the band.
That was another women in the band.
And that eventually came out of the St. Brad case, too.
The board was opposed to that.
And they did not want a gay student services organization on campus.
Were there, in those early years, among the board members, were there any that were more sensitive
to these matters than the others?
Any of the board members?
I'd have to.
Or I presume the problem was the other way.
It wasn't those who were sensitive.
It was those who were closed.
I'd have to go back and think about each one of the board members.
The thing that comes through loud and clear about that period of time was Dr. Williams said, relating to those issues, John, I don't want you dealing with the board.
I'll handle that, and I'll take care of that.
And so I really didn't have those kinds of discussions with individual board members.
And Dr. Williams kept that, which was good for me and a good way to have it.
Too often, you get
into a bad situation in regard to conversations that you have with a board member and saying things that maybe the president didn't want you to say or whatever, so did I.
Did you have incidents of where board members contacted you or somebody in your staff directly about many matters?
About housing all the time.
Oh, okay.
There, there.
Asking for... Uh-huh.
And I tried to take that load off of the president and so I tried to accommodate everyone that I could.
It was just part of the institution.
But that was no different than former students of any former student who was looking for help and support and a favor.
In those early years, which board members did you sense, from your point of view, were the most potent, the most powerful, the most influential?
Well, the beginning was Clyde Wells.
I thought Mr. Wells was very strong.
And in fact, when Dr. Williams eventually had his heart attack, I thought for a period of time that Mr. Wells was going to end up as chancellor of the institution.
So he was strong.
He was very, very nice to me.
Never pushed in any way until when Tom Parsons, I believe, yeah, Tom was...
Tom was the Chief of the University Police, if you remember, and he was going to retire.
Oh no, it wasn't.
If Tom was retiring as the Commandant, that's what it was.
And I had talked to Dr. Williams about the fact that I wanted Tom to take over as Chief of the University Police.
Director of Security.
I wanted him to be Director of Security.
Because Melcher was retiring and O.L.
was going to be chief of police.
I wanted Tom to be director of security.
Jack Williams thought I was just trying to find a place for Tom Parsons.
And I said, no.
Yeah, I argued that Tom was the man.
I thought Tom had Aggie orientation.
I thought he would be supportive.
I thought he could learn the police stuff that he knew.
Clyde Wells had a guy up in Allen, just north of Dallas, an Aggie, that he wanted me to hire as chief of police.
I went through the interview process my way, and I hired Tom.
But I wasn't unkind to either Mr. Wells or that guy, and he was a nice person, but he wasn't what I wanted in that particular position.
So that was the only time Mr. Wells ever kind of leaned on me a little bit, and it was simply because he thought this guy would be a good person for us to have.
But the relationship with Clyde Ross was good.
Clyde Freeman, I thought, was in a strong position then.
And it appeared that Clyde Freeman, for a while, might be a chance.
Of course, he was acting well while Dr. Williams was down.
It's amazing that John Kellum was never thought to be
or the person for that particular position.
And I'm not sure.
Of course, it wasn't privy to all the board meeting discussions why he wasn't considered.
Let's tackle the women in the Corps matter.
Women were in the Corps at the time you arrived?
No, that fall.
Yeah, that fall.
Describe how that progressed, that fall, as you recall.
The decision had been made by Tom and Stan and Dr. Williams that the women would not be totally integrated into all of the outfits and that they would be separated to live in their own dorm.
made it a little bit difficult at the beginning because had to have male officers for those units.
And that improved as it went along and having female leadership.
So it was male leadership and that created some problems.
Eventually, the fact that they were not integrated into all the units became a problem.
So we could have solved some problems to begin with,
that we integrated women into all units.
But in retrospect, back at that time and still, in regard to the difficulties of male and female, just the natural, normal kinds of interrelationships, I would do it the same way.
I wouldn't change it.
There comes a time when you can overcome that.
with the female leadership in those positions, leadership positions.
So that was a problem all that year, in fact for a couple years.
Do you remember any particular incidents, plus or minus?
The interesting thing about the Corps is that probably a hell of a lot more things happened than we ever became aware of.
And, you know, years later, the kids will, the adults will talk about the things that happened.
But I think, for the most part, it went, we didn't have a major incident, I'll put it that way.
Major incidents occurred later on, years to come, but during that first year, no major incident.
And I don't remember of any physical event where some male physically attempted to do something to a female.
We had, well, the physical things, crazy things to the core.
shaking hands with an upperclassman, that some of the male upperclassmen would not interact with the female fish.
And so that became a problem for us.
And when I say it became a problem for us, it became a problem for the Corps of Leadership and the Corps of Staff and civilian staff as well in regard to
getting people to understand we were integrating women into the Corps in every dimension.
They were going to have to do that or they weren't going to be a part of the Corps or part of the institution.
All right, the, and the women were in the Corps were all as freshmen to begin with and gradually moved up.
What was the next threshold after being in the Corps, what was the next threshold?
Fish drill team?
Yeah, that was much, much later, much, much later.
All right, I just want to follow up.
But in thinking now, one problem we did have
that just kind of popped up in my mind was that the Corps in the past had always handled discipline themselves and only as it related to the Corps.
After I came, discipline was a university matter and not just a Corps matter.
And so we had a problem with the military officers, military staff,
of letting us know about incidents and forwarding those individuals and their cases to us within the institution.
It wasn't simply a matter that because they were in a corps, it was a corps matter and
from their perspective, not an institutional matter.

So that became a problem for us and a problem we struggled with for a number of years because there was a tendency to believe that if it happened in the Corps, it ought to be kept quiet and in the Corps and not handled by the institution.
So we had to work through that.
Ron Blanchley was a key in all of that because Ron was primarily our disciplinary person back in that particular time.
So that was a major problem that we had to work through.
But in regards to the women, after leadership positions, then it became probably it wasn't
major item in terms of student organizations in the Corps until the females became juniors.
And then Ross Volunteers became a major source of the problem for us because
Those individuals to go into the Ross Volunteers were selected by upperclassmen.
Upperclassmen being all men had no interest in selecting a female to be a member of the Ross Volunteers.
So probably that was the, that came on bigger than anything else.
Melanie Zingratt was upset for a number of reasons.

one of which was not the Aggie Band, but as it played out, she indicated that, in fact, part of her lawsuit included the Aggie Band, that she had not been given the opportunity to participate in the Aggie Band.
That was really stretching her case, I thought, because she really had no interest in music and the band at that time.
But at least it answered everything for us, and when I say it answered everything,
One of the board members who was not an Aggie, and I mentioned his name in private, you've been out in public.
One of the board members said in no way would he ever allow as long as he was on the board.
He wanted to be in the Aggie band.
Now, Melanie Zantgraff, that's Z-I-N-T-G-R-A-F.
